josh already knows about this but basically if you take long to finish/a race condition, there's a very likely chance you get absolutely boned on the success rate calculation. Let's say you get blasted with 10 requests, ++attempted happens 10 times, then before you finish those 10 requests, let's say you only finish 4, ReportStats is called. 

your calculation is

4 completed / 10 attempted = 40%. But 5 seconds later you finish the other 6, so in reality your success rate was 100%, but now you have [0.40] in the SuccessRateOverTime array. 

so then another cycle happens and you have 

+6 that completed (which why completed sometimes exceeds attempted), but the same thing happens again, and you get another say 60% success rate and now you have [0.40, 0.60] average 50% success rate but in reality your success rate was 100%
this is why you see when you get blasted with a bunch (or for instance try and do 164k context ones) even if you do eventually respond to all of them

your success rate is guttered, in reality you were succeeding a lot more than you thought even with the engines running a bunch of requests it was just obviously slow from load, but not failing. however people that didn't get overloaded, whether it be they cached the response and were sending a ton of traffic they could cache, had a lot of gpus, or used an external api for overflow were able to maintain a high success rate as in general they were responding much faster than someone running > 2 requests on their nodes
its also why you'd make changes, add gpus,  setup monitoring, etc. and not notice an improvement, but also not detect any of these drops (because most weren't actually dropping)
